segments.text: were cackled okay and uh bull neck was meat all right now was ham bull neck also as far as i can remember bacon was bull neck
Yeah.
Any meat.
Any meat.
As I recall, that's been a long time ago, Haskell.
Was all dessert kush?
Yes.
That was the general term.
Pie, cake.
It was kush.
Okay.
Ketchup was blood.
Tea was horse.
Don't remember.
I think I intentionally have forgotten some of that stuff because it wasn't something that I wanted to remember.
Can you share with the machine any pranks, tricks you remember ever observing being played in the dining hall where somebody did something to somebody else's food?
They were always throwing food, and you had biscuits on the ceiling.
I thought that was part of the decoration.
But there was always harassing going on between tables and involving the food or involving the individuals.
But most people got in there and tried to get eaten and back to class.
Let's see.
We talked about your outfit.
How important, as you look back on it, how important was BAAA to you in your life?
Well, I think that was home, and you developed a very close relationship with the people that were in that unit.
They were difficult on campus, but you always had the feeling when we'd go on court trips and like that, the upperclassmen took care of you.
It became a very close-knit family unit, and certainly your fish buddies did.
We still get together regularly.
They come down here, Raul Fernandez, Billy Fernandez, Tommy Lowman,
Wesley Heald, so those guys that were in that unit, very close friends even today.
Do you remember any incident events during that freshman year that began to demonstrate that closeness?
Well, of course, we had to stick together during these hazing sessions.
And when we would go on court trips, those were the guys you stuck around with because you knew them well.
They became just like family.
And nobody, we had one car, Fish Burt had a pink Studebaker.
and out of those 43 that freshman year.
So we essentially had no car because 43 of us couldn't get in that pink Studebaker.
But we hitchhiked to ball games.
We had, every now and then you'd get a ride with an upperclassman.
It was a, it was a different world.
Can you describe your first court trip?
I didn't go to California on that first game.
I know a lot of the freshmen in the band went.
But the first court trip we hitchhiked to Fort Worth, I believe it was TCU, and marched at the game.
Of course, back then you went in as a unit to all the games, except basketball, where you had to alternate.
Aircroppers got every other home basketball game, and Army got every other one.

And we'd feel derogatory because you knew that you only had half the chance to see those games, and knowing that you were excluded made it important that you were there when you had the chance to be there.
Now, how did you get to Fort Worth for that court trip, that first one?
Hitchhiking.
Went over to the stand over at Northgate by the post office and got in line.
And you always made sure your bag had a Texas Aggie sticker on it.
And you'd get rides.
Sometimes you knew as soon as you got in you'd made a mistake.
Other times it was a delightful experience.
Met some very interesting people hitchhiking to Gaines and to Holm.
We're now including all of your years of experience in hitchhiking.
Share the highest and the lowest experience you remember in Aggie hitchhiking.
What?
Well, one Friday afternoon, I think it was just before Christmas because I knew I had some books with me.
Caught a ride with a fellow who was a dealer at Galveston in one of the
casinos down there, and he had just gotten a job in Las Vegas.
And he picked me up and said, do you have a driver's license?
Yes.
Driving a Cadillac.
I don't ever remember being in one until then.
He had worked all day, and so he wanted me to drive.
So I drove 428 miles to Wellington,
We got there just about sun up and mama invited him in and he slept for a couple of hours in bed and fed him breakfast and on he went.
Probably the most disappointing ride was when I caught a ride in a pickup with a farmer from Hearn.
Took about three hours to get to her.
And everything was passing us.
And he let me out on this side of town.
And you can't get a ride going north if you're on the south part of town.
That and experiences of getting a ride with someone that's drunk that won't let you drive.
And those are.
Did that happen a few times?
A couple.
No accident, but it was quite knuckle time.
But you never had a bad experience.
Not really.
I haven't found anybody yet that did.

I started hitchhiking when I was in high school because I worked at Plainview when I lived at Wellington in the summers before my freshman year and then between freshman and sophomore and sophomore and junior years in high school.
And I always hitchhiked over to Plainview and would hitchhike home.
And never had a few scary instances where people were drunk.
A couple that I vividly remember.
But by and large, you met some very interesting people.
Let's go back to court trips.
During all of your undergraduate years, describe some of the court trips and where you all stayed and some of the good times that you had.
Well, we nearly always stayed with the parent of one of the freshmen in our outfit.
And, of course, we slept on the vans and in the floor and what have you, always ate well.
And that might be how many, that one place?
10 to 15 of us, just wherever we could find a...
A open spot.
But that was fairly common back then.
Of the court trips, what was your favorite place?
I don't think I really had one.
I enjoyed the trip we drove when I was a senior to the Arkansas game.
But that wasn't a court trip, but you still went.
Yeah.
And left on Friday afternoon after we got out of labs and drove all night.
Stopped at Mount Pleasant Fish Messer's house and had breakfast.
Got into Arkansas, oh, about 11.
Dead tired and.
Some of the Arkansas students invited us to.
Come into the door.
And we slept for about two hours.
I was sleeping.
They shined our boots as a senior and.
Was just spectacular.
And we made that and then drove back after the game.
Can you remember any incredible, goofy, unbelievable events connected with going to some game somewhere?
Well, yeah, the TCU game when I was a junior.
Leaving the game, we got caught between the athletic dorm, and that's when the...
editor of the Aggieland that year.
He was a senior, got whooped.
And we got in a group, the Aggies did, surrounded by TCU students, and it took us about an hour to work our way on about three blocks to our vehicles.
I can't think of the military science professor, and he's still around here, that was kind of keeping us together.
But we had some experiences like that that you remember as being rather incredible.
All right, now let's go academic.
Early on, who did you turn to for academic advice and counsel?

uh dr gaines and dr little over in entomology g-a-i-n-e-s he was the head of the department dr little was the advisor student advisor for years and years i think he came here in about 1927. can you give some examples of the advice you got from them uh they just told you what courses you had to take needed to take
And, of course, they advised you as far as what electives to take.
They were good counsel when you got down, lonely when the whole world was picking on you.
They were valuable advisors at that point, as well as the Wesley Foundation Director of the church.
Were they available when you needed them?
Yes.
It was a much smaller place than it is nowadays.
It was much like a high school situation.
You could walk into their office and it was like talking to your dad.
Do you remember that?
You had respect for them and you had a little bit of, felt a little intimidated simply because of their position.
Do you remember?
Not the personality or how you were treated.
Remember how many freshmen there were your freshman year?
There were about 77 or 7800 total students at A&M.
And I would guess that when we first registered and official count was made is somewhere around 1200.
Because we would lose about half of them.
And you started out in entomology?
Yes.
You never changed your major.
Which is really unusual because I think I was either the first or second because most people had no idea what entomology was.
And most of them were recruited because entomology,
101 with introductory entomology was a required course essentially by everyone, even engineers.
Certain engineer majors took that as a science.
Who taught that?
Dr. Little.
And what was it like?
Describe that course.
Well, it basically dealt with the classification of insects and what their role in society today and
a little bit on controls and on behavior and habits.
There was no collection or anything like that required.
It was three hours of lecture.
And then you had one three-hour lab that you looked at insects, identified them, studied the biology, looked at the different life stages.
And you probably liked it.
Yes, but I liked some of the later courses that were more specific in terms of the introductory course is very broad, very general, has a lot of the whiz, bang, wow type information.
It was interesting.
But it wasn't challenging like some of the later courses that you took.
Some other courses that first year that were, you recall?
Well, you could say that freshman chemistry was a course that most guys in my class majored in.
They often took it each semester until they were seniors, and some of them never did pass it, but.
Who taught that course?
Was it Stubbs?
I know he taught chemistry.
I think that he taught.
Did y'all have a nickname for him?
Yes, but I don't remember it.
And it was a tough course?
For you?
No.
I was so scared of it going in that I spent a lot of time on it.
And so I only took freshman chemistry, both the inorganic, which was the first semester, and the organic second semester one time.
I was very fortunate.
English?
We had English literature.
We had history.
American history.
Who taught it?
Do you remember?
Zingaro taught our physics class, but that was sophomore year when I took the physics.
I took chemistry, history, English, biology.
Dr. Baldorf taught it.
in military science and PE.
And do you remember how you did that first semester academically?
I know that those first two exams tried to stay up all night and you don't do that because you go to sleep in the exams.
Not very well.
I made about a 42 on the chemistry exam and below 50 on
the math exam.
And figured out that there are better ways of approaching studying and getting rest and how to study.
So there were some trials.
But you passed everything the first semester?
Yeah.
I made one B.
The rest of them were A's.
Oh, oh.
You said not very well.
Oh, so you didn't spend it.
Quiz A, like to kill me, scared the life out of me.
I figured that I was probably going to be headed home at mid-semester.
But I probably would have to have a new one because I wasn't going to be welcomed as the one I'd left.
How often did you communicate with your parents?
About once a week, I wrote.
Mail was delivered in the door.
They put it on your door.
When I say they, we, as freshmen, the freshmen delivered mail.
It was brought in a sack and dumped in the guard room in each dorm, and then it was mail called.
They were delivered to the door.
Did your parents write to you?
Yes.
Mama did.
And Daddy told her what he wanted to say.
And about how often were there any phone calls between you and them?
I don't ever remember a phone call.
And where was the nearest phone to your room?
In the guard room.
There was one in the dorm.
And a freshman manned it, answered it, and another freshman was there.
You had phone duty.
And two people were assigned, two freshmen were assigned to be there.
And the schedule was worked out from about 6 in the morning until about midnight.
Surely you know that today's students cannot believe there wasn't a phone in every room.
Well, there was.
There was no air conditioning either.
That's right.
So you did well that first.
What led you, was it the high school preparation?
As you look back on it, what was the secret to your doing well academically?
Fear.
Someone asked me one time how I ended up going to college.
Mm-hmm.
And I really don't know.
I think it was just an undiscussed expectation in our home.
Both my mother, mother went to Tarleton and my dad went to Tarleton and then A&M.
I think it was just an expectation.
And I don't ever remember us discussing whether or not you would go to college.
What do you think would have been the result if you had announced to them that you had decided you would not go to college?
I think that I would have been overruled, but I don't know that.
When I said that to my dad about five years ago, he looked at me and he said, you knew damn good and well you'd have found a place to sleep that night.
But it was just an expectation, and it was not really discussed that that's what you, that was part of your getting an education.
Share with, when you mention your dad and Tarleton, share with me this machine, all that you can recall that he ever shared about Earl Rudder, his roommate?
Well, he and Earl...
Both were their own athletic scholarships.
And what an athletic scholarship was back then was the cow.
Someone had donated a cow to Tarleton.
And they, and this was the jersey, and they staked her out on the football field where she grazed.
And then they would bring her into the shower and milk her into the bottles.
Mm-hmm.
milk bottles that were glass, that were delivered to the faculty who paid for that milk, and that's their scholarship.
And they would wash the bottles out in the shower.
I don't know, they never had any refrigeration or anything, but that was probably the most interesting thing that I can remember.
Now, Mrs.
Rudder, in sharing that story,
story with me said that as she understood it from Earl the cow became available when Mr.
Rudder in the spring of his first year told the coach he was going to go back to Eden gonna drop out because he needed some money and that the cow then was made available
Does that say?
I wasn't aware of those details.
I just remember dad telling about their scholarship at Tarleton.
Were they the same year?
Yes.
Okay.
Graduated in 32, I believe.
And your dad had gone to what high school?
Roscoe, outside of Sweetwater.
What position did he play?
He was a halfback, and what he really was able to do at Tarleton to get enough money to stay there was he was a left-handed pitcher.
And on weekends, he would go out to Sol Ross.
There was a gentleman out there that was an avid baseball fan.
He had a semi-pro team, and they would pay $25 a game.
And so he would pitch either Saturday or Sunday.
Did your dad also do that in the summers out there?
Yeah.
And that's the reason he got a job during the Depression.
What position did, or football position, did Mr. Rutter play?
Do you know?
I don't.
He was either a center or a tackle.
Okay.
Do you remember your dad talking about Mr.
Rudder as a person, what kind of person he was like?
Well, he had a great deal of respect and admiration for Earl Rudder.
From his student?
From his student years, and then they stayed in touch.
He and Mrs.
Rudder
who, she told me that her name was Margaret, it wasn't Chick, so we better not put that in this text.
But I didn't know what her name was until I babysat with, when I was a student here with their kids when they would be gone.
And she was Chick, right?
I didn't know anything else.
That's what I've heard a number of others say.
And she told me here about 10 years ago, don't you ever call me Chick.
So I said, well, what do I call you?
And she said, Margaret.
She also told me that, she phrased it, Earl told her that one of the first times he delivered the milk to somebody,
the bottle wasn't quite full, and the man complained about that.
And she said that Earl said, well, there was a water faucet near where we, and from then on the bottle.
Made sure that it was full.
That it was full.
Did your father have any, share any memories about Mr. Rutter as a student?
Not that I ever recall.
Was he one of the group thoroughly?
Yes.
personality-wise and from a leadership standpoint.
Back then, he was one that led them in all kinds of trouble.
And did he make good grades?
I have no idea.
Grades were not discussed.
All right, let's come back then to academics for you.
During that freshman year, your interest in entomology never wavered.
It got stronger?
Well, of course, as most kids, when you come down here, you're not real sure of what you want to major in.
And I always entertained, thought, well, I might want to major in chemical engineering.
And so I kept that in mind and looked at it through my sophomore year, but never took it seriously.
And then in selecting electives, I took a number of economics courses, accounting,
international finance, business law, as electives, and did get a degree in economics along with my entomology.
Titium influenced that a lot, the actual getting a degree.
I was taking the courses over there, so I had interaction with a number of the staff members in economics.
Describe, summarize your recollections of Titium.
A very impressive person and very active on campus.
You heard and saw a lot of the man.
Very personable, very friendly.
Went out of his way to make sure that students were doing well.
Did they have any needs, any problems that he could help with?
Just someone that you said, now this is a mentor on this campus.
Now you said you majored in economics or ag economics?
Ag economics.
Did you have any economics courses?
Al Chalk, anybody like that?
Well, I think about half the course.
Accounting, I think, was taught over in economics rather than ag-eco.
Business law was taught over in economics.
Who was that?
I don't remember.
International finance was taught over in ag-eco.
So at the end of your freshman year, how did you feel about being an Aggie and your chances of survival?
Well, I was going to beat them before they could beat me.
And I think it's simply a matter of being pleased that you were able to survive that.
Always was impressed with the...
reputation of A&M in the Ag arena, and that was the one that I was most familiar with.
I got involved in a lot of campus activities outside the Corps and the outfit.
I was freshman class president, got involved in MSC, SCONA, and those took up a lot of time.
I was always
impressed here with how student government is run.
Go over there and you see the secretaries and you see these people's schedules.
And I remember as student body president or student senate president, as it was called back then, getting ready for a meeting and typing your agenda on the hunt and peck typewriter in your dorm.
and going over and getting Dean Penberthy to run off enough copies for all of the members of the Student Senate.
And you go over there now and it's bigger than the president's office was back then when Harrington and Rudder and them were in the president's office.
And it's run much more business-like and the amount of copies of stuff that are run off, the amount of help, the students,
ability to organize and to plan activities, just impressive the kinds of exposure they get and what you can get done.
Like comparing a manual typewriter to a computer today.
That's good.
That's very good.

Because I can remember even when I worked down here in the 60s and 70s, you'd type a manuscript for a publication, whether it was controlling cotton insects in Texas or how to requeen a honeybee colony.
You'd write the publication up,
And if you found a sentence on page 33 that was wrong, they had to retype pages 33 on the rest of the way.
Now you find that sentence in there, and they can do it before you wait right there at the desk, and they'll hand you the redone copy.
Let's zero in on the student leadership because that's the important part of the story.
How did you get to be freshman president?
Describe how that came.
Well, you asked a question a while ago about how did you get away from the dorm.
That's one way.
I had several upperclassmen in my outfit suggested that I ought to run.
I had someone running for every freshman class.
